    myStack.push(10);
    myStack.push(20);
    myStack.push(30);

    // Accessing the top element
    int topElement = myStack.top();
    std::cout  stack = new ArrayDeque<>();

        // Adding elements (push)
        stack.push(10);
        stack.push(20);
        stack.push(30);

        // Accessing the top element
        int topElement = stack.peek();
        System.out.println("Top element: " + topElement);

        // Removing elements (pop)
        stack.pop();
        topElement = stack.peek();
        System.out.println("Top element after pop: " + topElement);
    }
}
```

### Python

In Python, the built-in list structure can be used as a stack since it provides methods to add and remove elements from the end of the list (`append()` and `pop()` respectively), which align with the LIFO principle of a stack.

Here’s a simple example:

```python
# Using list as a stack

# Creating an empty stack
stack = []

# Adding elements (push)
stack.append(10)
stack.append(20)
stack.append(30)

# Accessing the top element
top_element = stack[-1]
print("Top element:", top_element)

# Removing elements (pop)
stack.pop()
top_element = stack[-1]
print("Top element after pop:", top_element)
```

### C#
```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        // Create a new stack of integers
        Stack stack = new Stack();

        // Push elements onto the stack
        stack.Push(10);
        stack.Push(20);
        stack.Push(30);

        // Peek at the top element without removing it
        Console.WriteLine("Top element: " + stack.Peek()); // Output: 30

        // Pop elements from the stack
        Console.WriteLine("Popped element: " + stack.Pop()); // Output: 30
        Console.WriteLine("Popped element: " + stack.Pop()); // Output: 20

        // Check if the stack is empty
        Console.WriteLine("Is stack empty? " + (stack.Count == 0)); // Output: False

        // Pop the last element
        Console.WriteLine("Popped element: " + stack.Pop()); // Output: 10

        // Check if the stack is empty again
        Console.WriteLine("Is stack empty? " + (stack.Count == 0)); // Output: True
    }
}
```

In all these examples, you can see the stack operations are very straightforward due to the convenience offered by the respective libraries.

In the upcoming lessons we will be using the libraries for the stack implementation.

Note that there are no default libraries for Stack in JavaScript, C and C#.

